om"},"nl":{"1103–1158":"1103–1158","1107–1169":"1107–1169","1135–1219":"1135–1219","1082–Male":"1082–Overleden","1082–1156":"1082–1156","1107":"1107","1103":"1103","1158":"1158","1169":"1169","1135":"1135","1156":"1156","about 1156":"circa 1156","1082":"1082","1219":"1219","Whitchurch, Shropshire, England":"Whitchurch, Shropshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk",", , Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shropshire, England","Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shropshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1103–1158":"1103–1158","1107–1169":"1107–1169","1135–1219":"1135–1219","1082–Male":"1082–Deceased","1082–1156":"1082–1156","1107":"1107","1103":"1103","1158":"1158","1169":"1169","1135":"1135","1156":"1156","about 1156":"about 1156","1082":"1082","1219":"1219","Whitchurch, Shropshire, England":"Whitchurch, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom",", , Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shropshire, England","Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Fitz","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Either a short form of any of the numerous names representing a transferred use of a surname formed with the Anglo-Norman French prefix <i>fi(t)z</i> ‘son of ’, as for example   Fitzgerald  ,   Fitzroy  , or a transferred use of the surname <i>Fitz</i>, which may be of the same derivation, but applied originally to distinguish a son from a father bearing the same given name, or a local name from Fitz in Shropshire, named with the Old English personal name <i>Fitt</i> + <i>hōh</i> ‘hill spur’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Ralph","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Ralf","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Fitz Ralph de Calverhall was born in 1103, in Whitchurch, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Randulph De Calverhall, was 21 and his mother, Mrs. Randulph De Calverhall, was 22. He had at least 1 son with Mrs. William de Calverhall. He died in 1158, in his hometown, at the age of 55."},"et":{"1103–1158":"1103–1158","1107–1169":"1107–1169","1135–1219":"1135–1219","1082–Male":"1082–Surnud","1082–1156":"1082–1156","1107":"1107","1103":"1103","1158":"1158","1169":"1169","1135":"1135","1156":"1156","about 1156":"umbes 1156","1082":"1082","1219":"1219","Whitchurch, Shropshire, England":"Whitchurch, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom",", , Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shr